Cosmological N-body simulations are an indispensable tool in modern astrophysics, providing the primary means to model the non-linear evolution of large-scale structure in the Universe. By tracking the gravitational interactions of a vast number of particles, these simulations bridge the gap between the primordial density fluctuations observed in the cosmic microwave background and the complex cosmic web of galaxies and voids seen today. The advent of large-volume galaxy surveys has created an unprecedented demand for these simulations. Generating large statistical ensembles, comprising hundreds or thousands of individual simulation runs, is now essential for accurately estimating covariance matrices, calibrating systematic effects, and interpreting observational data to constrain cosmological parameters with high precision.

This demand, however, confronts a significant computational bottleneck. High-fidelity cosmological simulations are exceptionally resource-intensive, with single runs often consuming millions of CPU hours. The sheer computational cost makes the generation of large simulation suites prohibitively slow, limiting the statistical power available for cosmological analyses. Overcoming this challenge is crucial for fully realizing the scientific potential of next-generation observational programs. A promising path forward lies in leveraging the massive parallelism of Graphics Processing Units (GPUs), which offer the potential for dramatic acceleration over traditional CPU-based architectures. Yet, developing efficient GPU code has historically required specialized, low-level programming expertise, creating a barrier to entry for many researchers.

In this paper, we explore a modern approach to this problem by developing a GPU-accelerated cosmological simulation using NVIDIA Warp, a Python-based framework designed to simplify the creation of high-performance GPU kernels. We implement a Particle-Mesh (PM) N-body code, an algorithm well-suited for modeling gravitational dynamics on large scales where it offers a favorable balance between computational efficiency and physical accuracy. Our implementation leverages custom Warp kernels for the critical particle-grid operations, namely the Cloud-in-Cell mass assignment and force interpolation steps, and utilizes a Fast Fourier Transform-based solver for the Poisson equation.

The primary goal of this work is to demonstrate that high-level frameworks like Warp can be used to build performant and physically reliable cosmological codes with reduced development complexity. To this end, we conduct a comprehensive evaluation of our implementation. We quantify the computational performance by benchmarking our GPU code against an equivalent multi-threaded CPU version, measuring the speedup achieved in each component of the simulation loop. Furthermore, we validate the physical fidelity of our simulation by comparing the final matter power spectrum against results from established, high-precision simulations. This work showcases the capability of our Warp-based code to rapidly generate mock universes, presenting a viable and accessible solution to help meet the growing computational demands of precision cosmology.

